Returns a dict in which keys are measure names, and values are the above numbers and sublists.

test_loading_batches()¶

Case when the batch size neatly divides into the number of samples. Example:

num-samples = 12 batch-size = 2 num-folds = 12/2 = 6 batches

In contrast to, say batch size 5, for which two full batches can be served, but two samples are left over. This case is tested in a separate test method

test_sampler()¶
test_some_batches_partly_filled()¶

Nasty case, when divisions between number of samples, batch size, number of folds, and distribution of classes does not come out well.

We use all samples, as usual: 12. Set batch_size to 3, and num_folds to 5. We get cases of 9 training samples, and 3 test samples:

When batches fit: 9 train, 3 test:

>>> fold_train_ids
array([ 2,  3,  4,  5,  7,  8,  9, 10, 11])

>>> fold_test_ids
array([0, 1, 6])
And:

When batches have one left over: 10 train, 2 test:

>>> fold_train_ids
array([ 0,  1,  2,  4,  5,  6,  7,  8, 10, 11])

>>> fold_test_ids
array([3, 9])

In this case, the number of full or partial batches for each of the five folds comes out like this:

Fold
1full batch

” <– Each batch is 3 samples, ” so 9 train, 3 test

2full batch
3full batch

” ” <– case of 10 train, 2 test 1

4full batch

1

5full batch

1

key_from_value(the_dict, sought_value=None, fn=None)¶

Given a dict, returns all of the dict’s keys that for which the value matches a given condition. The condition can either be a value, or a function that given a (key,value) tuple returns True if value meets the desired condition.

NOTE: should only be used for testing. If reverse

lookup is really needed, create a reverse dict instead.

Parameters

  • the_dict (dictionary) – dict to search

  • sought_value (any) – constant that is sought among the dict’s values

  • fn (function) – function(key_val_tuple) –> True/False

:returns list of keys for which dict[key] matches

the condition

:rtype hashable

query_yes_no(question, default='yes')¶

Ask a yes/no question via raw_input() and return their answer.

“question” is a string that is presented to the user. “default” is the presumed answer if the user just hits <Enter>.

It must be “yes” (the default), “no” or None (meaning an answer is required of the user).

The “answer” return value is True for “yes” or False for “no”.

download_call(rec, overwrite_existing, expected_go_ahead, expected_global_default)¶

Creates a temporary file, and calls download with the provided args. Then asserts expected_go_ahead and expected_global_default values.

Parameters

  • rec (XenoCantoRecording) – XenoCantoRecording on which to call download()

  • overwrite_existing (bool) – whether or not to overwrite

  • expected_go_ahead (bool) – whether resulting go_ahead should be True or False

  • expected_global_default – whether after the call the global default overwrite instruction should be True or False

:type expected_global_default:bool
